codex
**Short answer:** I did not find evidence that D3D11 is allowed to skip `w <= 0` clipping while D3D9 clamps it. Microsoft’s D3D11 spec says the clip volume includes `0 < w`, and even with `DepthClipEnable = FALSE`, hardware still performs `0 < w` clipping. The meaningful difference is that D3D9 exposes and this repo explicitly sets `D3DRS_CLIPPING = TRUE`, while D3D11 has no matching render state because rasterizer clipping is inherent and controlled only partly by `DepthClipEnable`.

**Spec-Level Findings**

D3D9:
- D3D9 primitive clipping is controlled by `D3DRS_CLIPPING`; Microsoft says setting it `TRUE` enables pipeline clipping, and it defaults to `TRUE`.
- D3D9 clip status docs say when clipping is enabled during drawing, Direct3D computes per-vertex clip codes.
- D3D9 also exposes guard-band caps in `D3DCAPS9`: `GuardBandLeft/Top/Right/Bottom` are screen-space guard-band coordinates.
- `D3DPMISCCAPS_CLIPTLVERTS` is specifically for clipping post-transformed vertex primitives; this repo does not query or branch on it.

D3D11:
- D3D11 clipping volume is documented as:
  - `0 < w`
  - `-w <= x <= w`, or wider if the implementation uses a guard band
  - `-w <= y <= w`, or wider if the implementation uses a guard band
  - `0 <= z <= w`
- `DepthClipEnable = TRUE` enables z clipping. If set `FALSE`, only z clipping is skipped; Microsoft explicitly says `0 < w` clipping still happens.
- Therefore, D3D11 guard band can defer/avoid **x/y** clipping, but it is not supposed to let `w <= 0` vertices survive to rasterization.

Sources:
- D3D11 rasterizer/depth clip docs: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/d3d11/ns-d3d11-d3d11_rasterizer_desc
- D3D11 functional spec clipping: https://microsoft.github.io/DirectX-Specs/d3d/archive/D3D11_3_FunctionalSpec.htm
- D3D9 primitive clipping: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/direct3d9/primitive-clipping-state
- D3D9 caps guard band: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/d3d9caps/ns-d3d9caps-d3dcaps9
- D3D9 `D3DPMISCCAPS_CLIPTLVERTS`: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/direct3d9/d3dpmisccaps

**Repo State Divergence**

D3D9 `gl05`:
- Enables normal clipping: [Direct3d9_StateCache.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_StateCache.cpp:91>) sets `D3DRS_CLIPPING = TRUE`.
- Disables user clip planes: [Direct3d9_StateCache.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_StateCache.cpp:103>) sets `D3DRS_CLIPPLANEENABLE = 0`.
- Sets `D3DRS_LASTPIXEL = TRUE`: [Direct3d9_StateCache.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_StateCache.cpp:57>).
- Initializes scissor off: [Direct3d9_StateCache.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_StateCache.cpp:122>).
- Sets viewport `MinZ/MaxZ` from caller: [Direct3d9.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9.cpp:3217>), fields at lines 3233-3235.
- Initial viewport is `0..1`: [Direct3d9.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9.cpp:1657>).
- Scissor support is cap-gated: [Direct3d9.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9.cpp:2005>), using `D3DPRASTERCAPS_SCISSORTEST`.

D3D11 `gl11`:
- Rasterizer defaults set `DepthClipEnable = TRUE`: [Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:747>), field at line 756.
- Scissor defaults off: [Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:757>).
- Rasterizer state is actually bound on draw when dirty: [Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:1446>).
- Viewport sets `MinDepth/MaxDepth` from caller and calls `RSSetViewports`: [Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:1716>).
- Initial frame viewport is `0..1`: [Direct3d11_Device.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_Device.cpp:701>).
- Render-target path also forces viewport depth `0..1`: [Direct3d11_RenderTarget.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_RenderTarget.cpp:268>).
- `supportsScissorRect_impl()` returns `false`: [Direct3d11.cpp](</D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11.cpp:215>), though `setScissorRect` exists.

**No W-Clamp Found**

I found no per-vertex `w` clamp, near-plane clamp, `SV_ClipDistance`, `SV_CullDistance`, `SetClipPlane`, `D3DUSAGE_DONOTCLIP`, or `D3DPMISCCAPS_CLIPTLVERTS` handling in either plugin path. The only relevant D3D9-only state is explicit `D3DRS_CLIPPING = TRUE`; the D3D11 port’s counterpart is `DepthClipEnable = TRUE`, which should still enforce `0 < w`.

So the repo divergence is real at the API surface, but the spec-level answer is: **D3D9 is not documented to do a special near-`w` clamp that D3D11 lacks. D3D11 may use a wider x/y guard band, but it still must clip `w <= 0`.**
